#import "template.typ": *

#let metadata = (
  title: "Basic Turning",
  unit: "Group A (3-Axis) | Phase 1 — Lesson 5 | E6, E8",
  author: "C.Moroney",
  version: "v1.0.0",
)

#let lesson = (
title: [Basic Turning]

,aim: [
Turn the aircraft to a preselected heading or reference point at a predetermined angle of bank, maintaining altitude and balance throughout.
]

,overview: [
The student integrates all previously established skills into coordinated turning flight. This lesson continues the attitude flying theme — a turn is simply another performance achieved by a specific attitude and power combination. Level turns at 15° and 30° AoB are introduced, followed by climbing and descending turns. The student manages adverse yaw, overbanking tendency, and altitude maintenance in the turn. Load factor is introduced at a basic level. The student conducts the takeoff independently with minimal instructor prompting, continuing E8 progression.
]

,learning_outcomes: [
#text(size:12pt)[*Knowledge*]
- Recall the four forces and their interaction in a level turn
- Explain how the horizontal component of lift provides centripetal force
- Describe adverse yaw and the need for coordinated rudder during roll entry and exit
- Explain overbanking tendency in level and climbing turns, and underbanking in descending turns
- Identify how parallax error causes errors when setting attitude during turns
- Introduce the concept of load factor and how it increases with angle of bank

#text(size:12pt)[*Skills*]
- Demonstrate entry, maintenance, and exit from level turns at 15° and 30° AoB
- Maintain altitude ±150 ft, airspeed ±10 kts, and heading within ±5° of target on rollout
- Apply coordinated rudder during roll entry and exit
- Complete climbing turns at 15° AoB and descending turns at up to 30° AoB
- Keep coordinated throughout
- Roll out onto a nominated heading or geographic feature

#text(size:12pt)[*Non-Technical Skills*]
- [SA] Thorough lookout before initiating each turn; continue LARI scan during the turn
- [TEM] Altitude loss risk in turns; spiral descent as a threat; terrain clearance maintained throughout
- [HF] Parallax error in roll; attitude differs between left and right turns — correct for it
- [CRM] Pre-turn lookout call
]

,theory_knowledge: [
- Aerodynamics — turning forces, load factor, skid/slip, climbing turns *(Pg 153, 165–168)*
- Human Factors — SA, stress, TEM *(Pg 3, 36–37, 43–51)*
]

,ground_brief_topics: [
Total time: 40 minutes \
Equipment required: Aircraft model, access to electronic briefing, whiteboard \

*Non-Technical Skills* (5 minutes)
- [TEM] Altitude loss in turns; spiral descent — causes and recognition; traffic in turn direction
- [SA] Lookout before and during turns; alerted see-and-avoid
- [HF] Parallax in left vs right turns; turning sensations and leaning tendency
- [CRM] Pre-turn lookout call and reference point selection

*Forces in a Turn* (10 minutes)
- Inclined lift vector: vertical component (maintains altitude), horizontal component (centripetal force)
- Backpressure required to increase total lift so vertical component equals weight
- Load factor introduction — at 30° AoB ~1.15; at 45° ~1.41

*Types of Turn* (10 minutes)
- Gentle turn (15° AoB), medium turn (up to 30° AoB), steep turn (45° or 60° AoB)
- Level turn: maintain altitude throughout; 15° and 30° AoB
- Climbing turn: limited to 15° AoB — reduced climb performance; overbanking tendency
- Descending turn: up to 30° AoB; underbanking tendency
- Exit from climbing or descending turn: level wings then correct power and attitude (PAT)

*Control Inputs in a Turn* (10 minutes)
- Entry: Bank (aileron to target AoB), Balance (rudder to counter adverse yaw), Backpressure (elevator to maintain altitude) — "3 Bs"
- Maintenance: minor aileron to hold AoB, rudder for balance, elevator for altitude — LARI scan
- Adverse yaw: up-going wing produces more drag; rudder in direction of roll counters
- Overbanking tendency in level and climbing turns; underbanking in descending turns

*Lookout Technique in Turns* (5 minutes)
- Pre-turn: opposite turn direction first, then forward, above, into and behind.
- In-turn: continue LARI scan; _briefly_ look into the turn for traffic
- Rollout: anticipate rollout
- Reference point: select a feature on the horizon before initiating; use it to control rollout
]

,ground_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Instructor*]
- Review weather, NOTAMs, and maintenance release with student
- Observe student completing operations whiteboard

#text(size:12pt)[*Student*]
- Participate in weather briefing and NOTAMs check with instructor
- Complete IMSAFE self-assessment and operations whiteboard
- Lead pre-flight inspection independently; complete documentation
- Conduct start, taxi, runup, and all checklists to takeoff
- Deliver pre-takeoff safety brief before taxi independently
]

,in_flight_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*E8 Takeoff Progression — Lesson 5*]
Student conducts takeoff with minimal instructor prompting. Instructor monitors silently; intervenes only if a safety issue arises. After-takeoff checks completed by student without prompting.

#text(size:12pt)[*Demonstration*]
- Adverse yaw: aircraft trimmed for S&L slow flight; apply aileron alone — demonstrate yaw opposite to aileron input
- Parallax: show difference in attitude reference between left and right turns
- 30° turn: same sequence; demonstrate overbanking tendency and correction
- 15° turn: Lookout, Bank, Balance, Backpressure — maintain ±100 ft, ±10 kts
- Climbing turn at 15° AoB: note reduced climb performance
- Descending turn at 30° AoB: note underbanking tendency

#text(size:12pt)[*Student Practice*]
- 30° turns left and right: maintain AoB ±5°, altitude ±150 ft, ball centred
- 15° turns left and right: maintain AoB ±5°, altitude ±150 ft, ball centred
- Deviation correction: recognise and correct altitude and balance deviations using LARI
- Rollout onto nominated heading or reference point: correct anticipation
- Climbing turns at 15° AoB: note effect on climb rate; exit with APT
- Descending turns at 30° AoB: note underbanking; exit to level with PAT
- Scenario task: "Perform 15° and 30° turns to track around a ground feature, maintaining 2500 ft with a clear lookout."
]

,common_errors:[
- *Looking into the turn*: Select a reference point before initiating; look _forward_ during the turn.
- *Altitude loss/gain in turn*: Check bank angle first — if correct, adjust backpressure and reference the horizon.
- *Uncoordinated entry/exit*: Rudder in the direction of aileron input during roll — not after. Squeeze the ball.
- *Overbanking beyond target*: Gentle opposite rudder to hold AoB
- *Poor pre-turn lookout*: Pre-turn lookout is non-negotiable — look, then turn
- *Pitch up when turning right*: Parallax error; horizon is in different position in left vs right turn
]

,post_flight:[
- *Student Self-Assessment* (5 min): Student describes what went well and challenges (e.g. "I kept losing altitude in 30° turns").
- *Instructor Feedback* (5 min):
  - Evaluate against completion standards (P, S, C, or NC).
  - Highlight strengths and areas for improvement.
  - Discuss TEM/SA: "Your pre-turn lookout was thorough, and you recognised the traffic threat."
- *Scenario Reflection* (5 min): "How would you adjust your turn technique to achieve the tightest possible turning radius?
- *Next Steps*: Assign homework.
]

,standards_for_progression:[
  #text(size:12pt)[*Progressing (P) — may advance to Lesson 6*]
- *Turn performance*: Bank angle ±5° of target, altitude ±200 ft, airspeed ±10 kts
- *Coordination*: Ball ±1/4 width with minor prompting
- *Rollout*: Within ±20° of nominated heading
- *Lookout*: Pre-turn lookout conducted with occasional prompting
- *Climbing and descending turns*: Entry and exit completed with minor instructor guidance
- *E8*: Takeoff completed independently; pre-takeoff brief delivered with minor prompting

#text(size:12pt)[*Solo Standard (S) — required before first solo*]
- *Turn performance*: Bank angle ±5° of target (S), altitude ±150 ft (S), airspeed ±10 kts (S)
- *Coordination*: Ball ±1/4 width throughout (S)
- *Rollout*: Within ±10° of nominated heading (S)
- *Lookout*: Conducts pre-turn lookout without prompting
- *Climbing and descending turns*: Demonstrates entry and exit; understands performance effect
- *E8*: Conducts takeoff with minimal prompting; delivers pre-takeoff brief before taxi independently
- *Outcome*: Recorded in student records (P, S, C, or NC) with comments.
]

,safety:[
- *Weather*: Horizon clearly visible, ceiling >2000 ft, wind \<25 knots
- *Altitude*: Conduct manoeuvres above 1500 ft AGL
- *Emergency Procedures*: Forced landing area pre-selected; EFATO brief completed
- *TEM*:
  - Monitor altitude closely
  - Monitor for spiral tendency if bank angle exceeds 30°
  - Monitor traffic before each turn; use alerted see-and-avoid
  - Maintain SA regarding training area lateral boundaries
  - Monitor for student anxiety, disorientation or airsickness; pause, assess and continue or cut lesson short if needed
]

,homework:[
- Read Bob Tait's RAAus Study Guide:
  - Aerodynamics: Pg 153, 165–168 (forces in turns, load factor, adverse yaw, skid/slip, climbing turns)
  - Human Factors: Pg 3, 36–37, 43–51 (TEM, stress management, SA)
- Reflect on lesson:
  - "How would strong turbulence affect your ability to maintain altitude in a turn?"
  - "How does load factor in a turn relate to the risk of stalling in the circuit?"

]
)

#show: body => lesson_plan(metadata, lesson, body)